<script>
const T=[
  {id:'eth',name:'Ethics & Standards',ico:'⚖',col:'#854F0B',bg:'#FAEEDA',sub:'Standards of Practice & GIPS',
   preview:{h:'Standards I–VII overview',p1:'This section covers the complete Code and Standards framework tested at CFA Level II, with emphasis on multi-part vignette scenarios across research ethics, suitability, priority of transactions and GIPS compliance.',p2:'Notes include side-by-side IFRS vs GAAP ethics tables, the standard violation detection framework, and 20 frequently tested exam traps.',f:'Violation detection: Intent + Knowledge + Harm → Standard mapping'},
   quiz:[
    {q:'Under Standard II-A, which activity is most likely permitted?',o:['Trading on a tip from a company insider','Combining public research with non-material non-public observations','Front-running clients after overhearing earnings guidance','Delaying MNPI disclosure to trade first'],a:1,e:'Mosaic theory allows analysts to combine public data with non-material non-public information to form investment conclusions — this does not violate Standard II-A.'},
    {q:'Standard III-C (Suitability) most requires a manager to:',o:['Execute client-requested trades immediately','Assess whether a trade fits the client IPS before executing','Refuse all speculative trades','Execute only with written client confirmation'],a:1,e:'Standard III-C requires suitability assessment against the IPS — risk tolerance, time horizon, and objectives — before executing any trade.'},
    {q:'Under GIPS, which portfolios must be in at least one composite?',o:['Top-performing portfolios only','All actual, discretionary, fee-paying portfolios','Only institutional portfolios','Portfolios with 3+ years of history'],a:1,e:'GIPS requires all actual, discretionary, fee-paying portfolios managed to a similar strategy to be included in at least one composite.'},
    {q:'Standard VI-B (Priority of Transactions) requires that:',o:['Members always trade before clients','Client transactions take priority over personal trades','All personal trades are prohibited','Members disclose all holdings annually'],a:1,e:'Standard VI-B mandates client transactions take priority over personal transactions. Clients must have first opportunity to act on recommendations.'},
    {q:'GIPS-compliant firms must present a minimum track record of:',o:['1 year','3 years','5 years building to 10','10 years from inception'],a:2,e:'GIPS requires a minimum of 5 years of compliant history, adding one year annually until 10 years is presented.'}
   ]},
  {id:'qnt',name:'Quantitative Methods',ico:'≋',col:'#185FA5',bg:'#E6F1FB',sub:'Regression, time series & machine learning',
   preview:{h:'Multiple regression & violations',p1:'Notes cover OLS regression, CLRM assumptions, F-test and t-test interpretation, R² vs adjusted R², and the full set of regression violations: heteroskedasticity, serial correlation, and multicollinearity.',p2:'Time series models including AR(1), unit root testing via Dickey-Fuller, and first differencing. Machine learning section covers supervised vs unsupervised learning, LASSO, and overfitting.',f:'AR(1): Xₜ = b₀ + b₁Xₜ₋₁ + ε · Mean-reverting if |b₁| < 1'},
   quiz:[
    {q:'High R² combined with individually insignificant t-statistics most likely indicates:',o:['Heteroskedasticity','Multicollinearity','Serial correlation','Model misspecification'],a:1,e:'Multicollinearity inflates standard errors of individual coefficients (making t-stats insignificant) while joint explanatory power R² remains high.'},
    {q:'A Durbin-Watson statistic close to 2 indicates:',o:['Positive serial correlation','Negative serial correlation','No serial correlation','Heteroskedasticity'],a:2,e:'DW ≈ 2(1−r̂). When r̂ = 0, DW = 2, indicating no autocorrelation. Values below 2 suggest positive serial correlation.'},
    {q:'An AR(1) model is mean-reverting when:',o:['b₁ = 0','b₁ = 1','|b₁| < 1','b₁ > 1'],a:2,e:'An AR(1) is stationary and mean-reverting when |b₁| < 1. When b₁ = 1, the series has a unit root and is non-stationary.'},
    {q:'LASSO differs from OLS primarily because it:',o:['Uses maximum likelihood','Adds an L1 penalty that can shrink coefficients to zero','Always produces higher R²','Requires no error term assumptions'],a:1,e:'LASSO adds λΣ|bᵢ| to the objective. This L1 penalty shrinks some coefficients to exactly zero, performing automatic variable selection.'},
    {q:'If a time series has a unit root, the remedy is:',o:['Adding more lag terms','First differencing the series','Using a longer sample','Removing outliers'],a:1,e:'First differencing (ΔXₜ = Xₜ − Xₜ₋₁) removes a unit root, converting a non-stationary I(1) series to stationary I(0).'}
   ]},
  {id:'eco',name:'Economics',ico:'◎',col:'#3B6D11',bg:'#EAF3DE',sub:'FX, trade policy & growth models',
   preview:{h:'Interest rate parity & exchange rates',p1:'Covers covered and uncovered interest rate parity, purchasing power parity, and the real exchange rate — including the mechanics of FX arbitrage and why CIRP always holds while UIRP frequently fails.',p2:'Trade section includes comparative advantage, terms of trade, Marshall-Lerner condition, J-curve, and trade restrictions. Growth section covers the Solow model with convergence implications.',f:'CIRP: F/S = (1 + r_d) / (1 + r_f) · No-arbitrage always holds'},
   quiz:[
    {q:'If domestic rates rise relative to foreign rates, the forward exchange rate (d/f) should:',o:['Increase — domestic at forward premium','Decrease — domestic at forward discount','Remain unchanged','Change only per PPP'],a:0,e:'CIRP: F/S = (1+r_d)/(1+r_f). If r_d rises, F increases — domestic currency at forward premium to prevent covered interest arbitrage.'},
    {q:'The J-curve effect refers to:',o:['Currency appreciation after a trade surplus','Trade balance worsening then improving after depreciation','Yield curve inversion','Inflation lagging monetary policy'],a:1,e:'After depreciation, import prices rise immediately while quantities adjust slowly. Over time export volumes rise and import volumes fall — creating a J-shape.'},
    {q:'In the Solow model, long-run per capita growth is driven by:',o:['Savings rate increases','Capital accumulation','Technological progress (TFP)','Population growth'],a:2,e:'Capital has diminishing returns in Solow — only technological progress (A) sustains long-run per capita GDP growth.'},
    {q:'The Marshall-Lerner condition states depreciation improves the trade balance if:',o:['Current account is in surplus','Sum of import and export demand elasticities exceeds 1','Inflation is below 2%','Capital flows are unrestricted'],a:1,e:'Marshall-Lerner: |ε_x| + |ε_m| > 1. When combined price elasticity exceeds 1, depreciation improves the trade balance after the J-curve passes.'},
    {q:'Uncovered IRP differs from Covered IRP in that UIRP:',o:['Uses forward rates','Is enforced by direct arbitrage','Relies on expected spot rates and often fails empirically','Assumes no capital mobility'],a:2,e:'UIRP is based on expected exchange rate changes and cannot be directly arbitraged. It empirically fails in the short run due to risk premiums.'}
   ]},
  {id:'fra',name:'Financial Reporting',ico:'▦',col:'#533AB7',bg:'#EEEDFE',sub:'Intercorporate investments & pensions',
   preview:{h:'Equity method vs consolidation',p1:'Notes cover the four methods of accounting for investments (fair value, equity method, proportionate consolidation, acquisition) with decision trees based on ownership percentage and degree of control.',p2:'Pension accounting covers funded status, periodic pension cost components, and the key IFRS vs US GAAP difference on remeasurements. Deferred tax section includes DTL/DTA recognition and valuation allowances.',f:'Equity method: Investment = Cost + Share of NI − Dividends − Impairment'},
